I was born with epilepsy and intellectual disability.
Growing up, I played hockey until I was 12 years old.
The longer I grew, the more I felt it was harder to keep up with others, and I was irritated and frustrated.
For a while, I didn't practice any sports, had no friends, and felt forgotten and sad.
There was a time when people with intellectual disabilities were hidden from society.
No one thought they they could practice a sport, and even less be an important member of society.
In the 1960s, Dr. Frank Hayden, a scientist at the University of Toronto, studied the effects of regular exercise on the physical condition of children with intellectual disabilities.
Using rigorous scientific research, Dr. Hayden and other researchers concluded that it was simply the lack of opportunity to participate that led to physical condition issues.
Many people doubted that people with intellectual disabilities could benefit from fitness programs and sporting competitions.
But pioneers like Dr. Hayden and Eunice Kennedy Shriver, the founder of the Special Olympic Games, persisted, and the athletes of the Special Olympic Games proved them right half a million times.
Before joining the Special Olympic Games, I was nervous because I was young, shy, and had little confidence in myself and I had not many friends.
When I arrived, however, everyone greatly encouraged me, supported me, and allowed me to be myself without being judged.
Now, I am a basketball player and a speed skater who competed in regional, national events, and this year finished at the Summer World Championships in Los Angeles, where I was part of the first ever Canadian basketball team to participate in the World Championships.
I am one of the over four and a half million athletes worldwide, and I have heard so many similar stories.
Being a Special Olympic Games athlete restores pride and dignity.
The Special Olympic Games also address significantable health needs.
Studies have shown that, on average, men with intellectual disabilities age 13 years younger than those without, and women with intellectual disabilities age 20 years younger than those without.
The Special Olympic Games keep us healthy, make us active, and involve us in sports.
Furthermore, our coaches teach us about nutrition and health.
The Special Olympic Games also provide free screening tests for athletes who have difficulty communicating with their doctor or accessing medical care.
At the 2015 Summer World Championships, my Canadian teammates and I played against the Nigerian team.
The day before our game, the Nigerian basketball team had come for the screening of World Championship athletes. Free distribution was given to seven members on the 5th and they had the chance to hear clearly for the first time.
This change for them was was incredible.
They were very excited, happy, and confident, as their coaches could communicate orally with them.
And they were very moved because they could hear the sounds of the basketball, the whistle sounds, and the enthusiastic fans in the stands - sounds that we take for granted.
